COVID_19_Analysis_w_recoveries

COVID 19 Analysis with recoveries

In the previous R analysis (COVID19 Basic Time Series Analysis), we reviewed the initial stage of COVID19 spread and recoveries were not taken into consideration. At this point in time (May 1st 2020), that more information about recoveries has been made available we will study the effect of these on the number of hosital beds required. It will also provide a complementary view into mortality rate and potentially how the mortality rates is reduced as the virus spreads more and more.

The focus will be the US, but for reference information from Singapore, South Korea and Germany will be used as well.

Modify previously defined function to accept Recovered data.

#Returns a Dataframe to use in Ggplot that 
library(ggplot2)
Estimated.Daily.Infections.Country <- function(Confirm.Daily, Death.Daily , Recovered.Daily, Country.Terr, State=NA, Lag=14 , Mortality=0.01){
  # Have to add checks in the future. Currently it works with Exact Matches
  library(reshape2)
  
  if (is.na(State)){
    Country.Confirmed = Confirm.Daily[Confirm.Daily$Country.Region == Country.Terr,]
    Country.Deaths = Death.Daily[Death.Daily$Country.Region == Country.Terr,]
    Country.Recovered = Recovered.Daily[Recovered.Daily$Country.Region == Country.Terr,]
  }else {
    Country.Confirmed = Confirm.Daily[Confirm.Daily$Country.Region == Country.Terr & Confirm.Daily$Province.State == State,]
    Country.Deaths = Death.Daily[Death.Daily$Country.Region == Country.Terr & Death.Daily$Province.State == State,]
    Country.Recovered = Recovered.Daily[Recovered.Daily$Country.Region == Country.Terr & Recovered.Daily$Province.State == State,]
  }

  #confirmed transform into long format
  Country.Confirmed$Statistic = "Confirmed"
  
  Country.Confirmed.Long = reshape(Country.Confirmed,varying = colnames(Country.Confirmed[,5:(dim(Country.Confirmed)[2]-1)]),v.names="Confirmed",idvar=c("Province.State","Country.Region","Lat","Long","Statistic"),direction="long")
  #Add corresponding date to Count
  Country.Confirmed.Long$Date_Name = colnames(Country.Confirmed[,5:(dim(Country.Confirmed)[2]-1)])
  
  #transform recovered to long
    Country.Recovered$Statistic = "Recovered"
  
  Country.Recovered.Long = reshape(Country.Recovered,varying = colnames(Country.Recovered[,5:(dim(Country.Recovered)[2]-1)]),v.names="Recovered",idvar=c("Province.State","Country.Region","Lat","Long","Statistic"),direction="long")
  #Add corresponding date to Count
  Country.Recovered.Long$Date_Name = colnames(Country.Recovered[,5:(dim(Country.Recovered)[2]-1)])
  
  #create Dataframe for Deaths. Transform into long format
  
  
  
  Country.Deaths$Statistic = "Deaths"
  Country.Deaths.Long = reshape(Country.Deaths,varying = colnames(Country.Deaths[,5:(dim(Country.Deaths)[2]-1)]),v.names="Deaths",idvar=c("Province.State","Country.Region","Lat","Long","Statistic"),direction="long")
  
  #Add corresponding date to Count
  Country.Deaths.Long$Date_Name = colnames(Country.Deaths[,5:(dim(Country.Deaths)[2]-1)])
  Country.Deaths.Long$Estimated_Infections = NA
  #Deaths is a 14 lag to infections. 1% Mortality rate. Have to start from row 15
  ##Maximum Lag will be 14
  if (Lag >15 ) Lag=14
  #Have to add limits to morality rate >0 and <=1
  Country.Deaths.Long[c(1:(dim(Country.Deaths.Long)[1]-Lag)),"Estimated_Infections"] = Country.Deaths.Long[c((Lag+1):dim(Country.Deaths.Long)[1]),"Deaths"]*(1/Mortality)
  
  #merge deaths and confirmed
  
  Country = merge(Country.Confirmed.Long,Country.Deaths.Long[,c("Date_Name","Deaths","Estimated_Infections")],by="Date_Name")
  #add Country recovered Country.Recovered.Long
  Country = merge(Country,Country.Recovered.Long[,c("Date_Name","Recovered")],by="Date_Name")
  Country = Country[order(Country$time),]
  
  #add dates in right format. Convert Date_Name
  
  Country$Date = as.Date(substr(Country$Date_Name,2,nchar(Country$Date_Name)),format ="%m.%d.%y")
  #change  for ggplot
  
  Country.Long = melt(Country[c("Date","Confirmed","Deaths","Estimated_Infections","Recovered")],id="Date")
  #update names
  colnames(Country.Long) = c("Date","Statistic","Count")
  #calculate linear regression with last 5 values of Estimated infections
  Est.Infect.reduced = Country.Long[Country.Long$Statistic=="Estimated_Infections",c("Date","Count")]
  #only 5 values prior to NA
  temp = min(which(is.na(Est.Infect.reduced$Count)))
  
  lm.infect = lm(Count ~ Date, data=Est.Infect.reduced[c((temp-5):(temp-1)),])
  #predict for missing dates and append to Es.Infect.reduced
  
  #predict based on 5 last records and add to NAs as probable number of  infections. Directly to 
  
  #predict(lm.infect,newdata=data.frame(Date=Est.Infect.reduced[is.na(Est.Infect.reduced$Count),"Date"]))
  #Est.Infect.reduced[is.na(Est.Infect.reduced$Count),"Date"] = predict(lm.infect,newdata=data.frame(Date=Est.Infect.reduced[is.na(Est.Infect.reduced$Count),"Date"]))
  Country.Long[Country.Long$Statistic=="Estimated_Infections" & is.na(Country.Long$Count),"Count"] = predict(lm.infect,newdata=data.frame(Date=Est.Infect.reduced[is.na(Est.Infect.reduced$Count),"Date"]))
  
  return(Country.Long)
  
}

# Get counts of total deaths for latest date
Deaths.US.Recent = Deaths.US[,c(1:12,dim(Deaths.US)[2])]
#order decreasing by County

Deaths.US.Recent=Deaths.US.Recent[order(Deaths.US.Recent[,13],decreasing=TRUE),]

Total.D = sum(Deaths.US.Recent[,13])
Total.P = sum(Deaths.US.Recent[,12])

Deaths.US.Recent$Perc_all_US = Deaths.US.Recent[,13]/Total.D
#cummulative percentage
Deaths.US.Recent$Cummu_Perc = cumsum(Deaths.US.Recent$Perc_all_US)

#Deaths in 100 out of 3,200+ Trerritories and counties make up 80%. 8 Make up 50%. 20 make more than 63%

# Show top 10 Locations with % of all US Deaths

#have to reorder labels
Top_10 = Deaths.US.Recent[1:10,]
#reorder. Changed combined Key to factory
Top_10$Combined_Key = as.factor(Top_10$Combined_Key)
#reorder factor according to ort of dataframe
Top_10$Combined_Key = factor(Top_10$Combined_Key, levels = Top_10$Combined_Key)

Top_10$Percent = paste(round(Top_10$Perc_all_US,3)*100,"%",sep="")

ggplot(Top_10, aes(x=Combined_Key, y=X5.1.20, fill = Combined_Key))+geom_bar(stat="identity") + labs(subtitle="Source: John Hopkins University. Percentage shows ratio to total deaths in US",
         title= "Coronavirus - Cummulative Number of Deaths by County - Top 10 - May 1st 2020") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "BrBG") + xlab("County") + ylab("Number of Deaths") + geom_text(aes(label=Percent), position=position_dodge(width=0.9), vjust=-0.25)

Now Calculate the mortality rate by Age Group based on Information from New York State and estimated number of Infections. https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/NY/PST045219 Persons under 5 years, percent 5.8%

Persons under 18 years, percent 20.8%

Persons 65 years and over, percent 16.4%

This can be used to calculate the mortality rate by age group.

About 1.9 million were Infected in NY State (around 4/10). Based on John Hopkins University Information and a Mortality rate of about 1.1% overall (with a lag of 13 days). This is in line with estimated reported by the Wall Street Journal stating that more than 2 million people had been infected by COVID 19 as of April 23rd - this was based on an anti-bodies test.

~80% of the deaths are for people over 65 years old but they make up only 16.4% of the population in New York. Ratio of 4.87 deaths for people over 65 to people under 65 when infected

Number of deaths 20,973 as of 4/23, Of those 80% (16778) were people over 65. Estimated number of people infected in that age group were 311,600 around 4/10. So an estimated mortality rate for this age group is 5.3%.

For people under 65 (1,588,400) the mortality rate is about 0.26% based on an estimated number of deaths of 4,195. With most of the deaths falling in the group between 45 and 64 years old.

To be more accurate 20.8% of all population is under 18 years old and the number of deaths under this category is neglible. The total number of deaths will stay about the same around 4,195 but the poulation between 18 and 65 corresponds to 62.8% which would be about 1,193,200 of all infections. So the mortality rate in the group between 18 and 64 years old is 0.35% ; under 18 (even under 25) the mortality rate is very close to zero (probably lower mortality rate than Infuenza)

Have to calculate total percentage of deaths by Age group

CDC_Age_Perc = CDC_Age[2:12,c("Indicator", "Perc_Covid_Deaths" )]

CDC_Age_Perc1_24 = data.frame(Indicator="0-24 years",Perc_Covid_Deaths=sum(CDC_Age_Perc$Perc_Covid_Deaths[1:4]))

CDC_Age_Perc= rbind(CDC_Age_Perc, CDC_Age_Perc1_24)
#remove first 4 rows

CDC_Age_Perc = CDC_Age_Perc[5:12,]
#change column names

colnames(CDC_Age_Perc) = c("Age_Group","Perc_of_COVID19_Deaths")
#order

CDC_Age_Perc=CDC_Age_Perc[order(CDC_Age_Perc$Age_Group),]


CDC_Age_Perc$Percent = paste(round(CDC_Age_Perc$Perc_of_COVID19_Deaths,3)*100,"%",sep="")

ggplot(CDC_Age_Perc, aes(x=Age_Group, y=Perc_of_COVID19_Deaths, fill = Age_Group))+geom_bar(stat="identity") + labs(subtitle="Source: CDC. Percentage shows ratio to total COVID 19 deaths by Age Group",
         title= "Coronavirus - Confirmed Deaths by CDC as of - April 25th 2020 - reported on May 1st") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "BrBG") + xlab("Age Group") + ylab("% of Total Number of Deaths") + geom_text(aes(label=Percent), position=position_dodge(width=0.9), vjust=-0.25)

It is clear that based on previous analysis that focusing on protecting elderly population in New York City and other major metropolitan areas with high population density could reduce the number of Deaths by 40% or more going forward.
